div.p:
In the rage for novelty, it is unpleasant to perceive that virtue must be new-fashioned to be acceptable: those qualities which adorned our grandmothers are wholly rejected--and rejected as if they were worn out and unfit for use;
whereas,

whereas, if they were impartially examined, it would be found that they might adorn the female character even at this day of improvement, that they might add virtue to elegance, and render her respectable who is already amiable.
